      <hedline>
        <hl1>Boorishness Knows No Race</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dorothy M Broderick letter responds to Peter Applebome's July 30 column on loud, obscene rap music being played by man at gas pump (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>I have only a smidgen of sympathy for Peter Applebome, who wrote of his encounter with a black man blasting obscenity-laced rap music from his car [''What Would You Have Done?'' Opinion, July 30].</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>I have only a smidgen of sympathy for Peter Applebome, who wrote of his encounter with a black man blasting obscenity-laced rap music from his car [''What Would You Have Done?'' Opinion, July 30].</p>
        <p>I live in a middle-class neighborhood where teenagers, all white, gather after 10 p.m. and play rap for hours. Their shouts are filled with profanities and the bass from the car stereos means the pictures on our walls must be straightened several times a week. I'd willingly trade Mr. Applebome's brief encounter for what goes on around here, and race is totally irrelevant.</p>
        <p>DOROTHY M. BRODERICK  East Patchogue</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
